            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            My Path to Faith
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            evelyn li
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">
            I guess I am more of a thinker and deliberator than a feeler. When I was first introduced to Christianity I was five years old, and my grandmother was a Christian, a Protestant. She took me to her church. I didn’t like the people there, but I remember every time Christmas came I would get beautiful presents from them. As a child in Hong Kong, that was very, very extraordinary. It was such a special occasion for us because no one gave us candies at all. Christmas was really a candy day. The first time we ate candies was once a year at Christmastime when we would go to church. So who doesn’t like Christmas and who doesn’t like the Church? That was the first time I was introduced to Christianity.<br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/120529306" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “I woke up and said, ‘God has been nice to me all this time, and I have not been nice to him. What happened to me?’”
                </span>
            </div>
            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
            Then I was put into a Catholic elementary school. I read about Jesus in our textbook. It talked about Jesus feeding 2,000 people and making someone dead come alive. I said, "How could anybody not believe in him?" Even the story of Jesus walking on water, how could anybody not believe in this person? I had never heard of anybody who could walk on water. That’s Jesus. I kept looking at the book and I kept looking at the people. I said, "Why don’t you guys believe? They’re teaching us that Jesus walked on water. Why are you not making a big deal out of it?" As a concrete thinker, I could not understand for a moment why anybody would not believe in Jesus. <br /><br />
            </span>
            <span id="Exclusive_Quote_Mod">
            “My grandmother was a devoted Christian, but she never preached about it. She never talked to us about it.”
            </span>
            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">So I believed in Jesus, but I did not like my elementary school. I did not like the Catholic Church at the time. I was not baptized in the Catholic Church, but I was a student there. The reason I didn’t like it was that they would put us under the hot sun for hours to say prayers to Saint Mary. One or two times I actually fainted, and a lot of my classmates also fainted in the hot Hong Kong summertime sun. I said, “If there’s a nice God in this church, why would they want us to suffer like that as a little child?” I didn’t believe in any doctrines from then on. There were some doctrines in the Catholic Church I wasn’t very fond of. One of them was that we are always a sinner. As a child it was hard for me to understand why all of a sudden we had sinned so much. What did we do? That was not explained well to us.<br />

            <br />When I moved to Hawaii I still didn’t believe, because my dad was an atheist, my mom was an atheist, and though my grandmother was a Christian, but she rarely went to church. When we came to Hawaii, things were rough. We didn’t have any friends and the people that we knew were Chinese gangsters. They smoked and did all kinds of things like take drugs. There was not much Christianity in our circle of friends.<br />
            </span>
            
            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory0-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory0');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory0" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                When I was fourteen years old, because of the adverse situation in our family, we were latchkey kids: inside the house and our parents not around. We lived in the ghetto. The teenage boys out there frightened us, and my parents were always working. We were totally petrified in that kind of environment. I sat down and prayed to God for two hours, and I cried for two hours. I remember hearing a voice from an angel, and he told me, "You have to work hard." I felt like that was my holy spirit, because ever since that time he was always with me. I felt like every time I got A’s, it was because of him. Being as poor as we were, we couldn’t afford a tutor, but I could comprehend things so fast. He basically taught me how to get A’s in school and he taught me how to study. It was amazing. I suddenly felt like I had more intelligence than I ever had before. I felt like this same spirit coached me to study and taught me how to understand what I was learning. Ever since that time, I could excel in everything I tried. That was my touch with the spirit world. <br />

                <br />Then, when I was seventeen, my sister converted to Mormonism and was baptized. When I turned seventeen I had nothing to do, so I remember going with her to the church. The missionary talked to me and asked, "Do you want to go back to heaven? That’s where you came from." I said, "Oh, totally! It sounds so right and so true, why not? If that’s the only thing it takes to go back to heaven, then I'll do it. I'll get baptized." So I was baptized when I was seventeen. <br />

                <br />Needless to say, I wasn’t a pious or devoted person. My sister was very devoted and she went and served a mission, which I wish I had done. But you know, you always make mistakes in life. I didn’t serve a mission. But I was very pampered by God. He knew that I was rebellious. He managed to straighten me out, but he pampered me at the time. He let me go to college and medical school and get free rides. He also gave me the best man in the world, and we got married and had three great children. They were just wonderful kids. I was so pampered by God that I felt like I just didn’t deserve it. <br />

                <br />One day, when God took my husband away from me, it was the collapse of my world. I woke up and said, "God has been nice to me all this time, and I have not been nice to him. What happened to me?” I realized that when the Holy Spirit was slowly running away from me, I felt different. I wasn’t as intelligent as before; I wasn’t as powerful as before; I was beginning to be weak and scared; it was not me anymore. I began to search again, to search for the purpose of living. Especially because my husband, 33 years old, just out of medical school, and only a doctor for two years, and God took away his life. At that moment I said, "What is the purpose of life? Why was he only here for a few years and then died? Why is this happening?" I was searching for the meaning of life. <br />

                <br />Don’t forget that at that time I had been inactive in the church for ten years. My sister was very nice. She has always been the angel of my life. She told the missionaries to come and visit me again. As rebellious as I was, I didn’t want to be forced or pushed into any religion. They were very nice. They left me The Book of Mormon, Gospel Principles, and The Doctrine and Covenants in my mailbox because I hung up on them so many times that they knew I didn’t want to talk to them. <br />

                <br />During the time right before my husband died, I had nothing to do except sit next to him, because he was on chemotherapy. When I was sitting next to him I had nothing to read, so I picked up that book and I read the whole book: The Book of Mormon, The Doctrine and Covenants, and all the other books I could get my hands on to understand the purpose of life. In The Doctrine and Covenants, I came across the concept of the three degrees of glory. That all made sense to me. God also said, “You live with a purpose, you’re born with a purpose, and you die with a purpose.” All of these things made so much sense to me. I said, "O, my God! My eyes have been opened! There’s a reason to be born, and there’s a reason to live." After I read that book, I totally converted. I said, “There is no other church other than this church. This has to be the true church because that is wisdom. That is intelligence. That is what life is all about. We have an eternity. We have a future. This life is only temporary.” <br />

                <br />When I saw the truth in it, nobody could take that away from me because it was true. My husband also was baptized, and then he died. I became active again in the church, and I have been very faithful ever since. I subsequently became the Relief Society president in Oakland. I was very proud of myself. I was progressing in a better direction.

                </span>
            </div>
        </div>


