            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            Dreams of My Biological Father
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            kimberli cheung
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">After my dad passed away, when I had barely turned six, we moved from Sacramento to Concord. I remember the first while it was really lonely. All of sudden I didn’t have attention from both parents. All of a sudden we didn’t have any attention from either parent because Dad had passed away and Mom was busy working all the time. 
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/121174102" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “I opened the door, it was the middle of the night, and my biological father was floating there in front of me, maybe about a foot above the ground.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
            One night I had a dream. It was knocking of some sort, or a doorbell ringing at the door. I really thought it was real in my dream. I went to the front door and opened the door. I know it sounds crazy because I was only six, but I opened the door, it was the middle of the night, and my biological father was floating there in front of me, maybe about a foot above the ground. I don’t know why. <br />

            <br />I was so excited and happy to see him. I didn’t have any fearful feelings or thoughts at all. They were very elated, happy feelings. He talked to me and asked me how I was doing. He asked me how first grade was going and I was so excited to tell him all about my life, all that was happening, and that I missed him so much. I remember that I woke up and it wasn’t real. <br />
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                Years later my mom told this story that she was in the same house, the one in Concord, and that she had a dream shortly after my dad’s death. It was probably around the same time period that I was having my dream. She said that she heard a knocking or doorbell ring at the door, and she went to the door, answered it, and it was my dad. She was so excited to see him. He was floating above the ground and he talked to her about how wonderful heaven was and the spirit world. She invited him into the house and he said he could not. She doesn’t know why, but he explained that he wasn’t allowed to. <br /><br />

                He invited her to come out of the house, so she walked out of the house and they floated to the top of a fence somewhere and stood on the top of the fence and held hands and talked about all of the wonderful things in the spirit world: the amazing mysteries and abilities that you can all of a sudden do and have when you’re up there, and the beautiful scenery and colors. He shared all of this with her. <br /><br />

                I can’t remember exactly all of the details, but I remember my biological father pretty well in my own way, and he was always uplifting. He was always encouraging. I knew that from personal experience. He was this all-around really positive person. He instilled strength in people. He taught me how to ride my first bike. I can only imagine that he, in that moment, strengthened my mom and told her, “You can do this,” and made her feel confident in herself that she was not alone, that he was there and that God was watching over us.<br />
                </span>
