            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                His death was very traumatic for me. After he died, I felt like I had no friends in this world. I felt so alone. Not to mention facing financial problems, and the work was tremendous, taking care of three kids with two babies in diapers. Time-wise, I couldn’t face it. Plus, at that time I was still in training as a doctor. All of that created extraordinary hardship for me. It was a difficult time. <br /><br />
                </span>

                <span id="Exclusive_Quote_Mod_in_SM">
                “I was six years old when my dad passed away and I've seen my mom grow from being more of a submissive wife, when I did have my biological father around, to becoming more of an independent woman who started to have opinions and started to look for values, a reason, and a purpose to live.” - Kimberli Cheung, daughter
                </span>

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                The second time, when my second husband left me, it was devastating because I would never have thought he would leave me because we were married in the temple, we were both Mormons, and it wasn’t part of the equation that you get married just to go through a divorce. It was never in the equation that he would leave. We thought we could always work things out. <br /><br />

                When he left me for another woman, it was devastating for me. I didn’t understand why. I didn’t understand why he did what he did. I thought I was a good wife. I thought I provided everything. I cleaned the house, I took care of his business, I took care of the swimming pool, I took care of the back yard, I took care of the three kids. He didn’t have to do practically anything. I took care of all the finances. I was also a full-time doctor, a cardiologist. I thought he would appreciate that. Yet he still left me. It was a lesson to learn. <br /><br />

                I thought, “Where is God? Why is he not with me? What is going on here?” I think part of growing up is asking, “What it going on?” Someone pulls the carpet out from underneath your feet. All of a sudden your best friend is no longer your best friend. All of a sudden I saw myself with lawyers in between us. We became enemies. Not until a year later did I succumb myself to God. I humbled myself and said, “Well, it could be me that is creating this estrangement. It could be me.” Then I began to have peace. <br /><br />

                Looking back at it right now, I wouldn’t say it’s fully his fault that he left. I would say it’s partly my fault that we didn’t communicate at that time. I was overworked. I was too tired to talk to him and we no longer communicated, so he was looking for another woman to communicate with him. That may be part of the issue. I wasn’t a lovey-dovey type of person. I’m not a very sentimental person, so people may feel coldness in me. Compassion was never nurtured in me. So this helped me understand how other people can be different from me. They might need more physical touch or love that I’m not giving. They have different thinking than you do, other needs than you do. It made me become a better doctor. I became a better listener. <br /><br />

