            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory3-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory3');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>
            <div id="restofstory3" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                After my marriage, it was just like all marriages; it has its ups and downs and challenges. One of my challenges was that what I wanted was frequently not what my husband wanted. For example, he didn’t want a maid in the house. For me, facing three children, it was difficult. But he did allow my parents to live with us, and so my parents helped us out. But my parents were getting older and older, it was becoming more and more difficult. It got to the point where my parents were constantly yelling at each other and yelling at me, disrupting a lot of the peace in our home. On top of my challenges at work, I had to tell my parents, “You have to move out, because we cannot constantly be having fights at home.”<br /><br /> 

                After my parents moved out, I was again facing a difficult situation. I had a lot of work to do, a lot of housework to do, and my husband also had a lot of work to do in his office, so he was tired when he came home and couldn’t help me. Out of strenuous activity and working, I had three miscarriages. I was taking care of the children myself, doing my church calling, plus my office work; it put a lot of strain on our marriage. My husband decided, “This marriage is not right for me.” He left. He left our family. He left with my secretary that I hired for him. At that point in time I was devastated and sad. A year later he decided to come back. <br /><br /> 

                During that whole year, a lot of things came into my thoughts: “What did I do wrong? What could I have been better?” I scrutinized my thoughts and this whole event actually made me closer to God. I wanted to know what was happening and why this was happening to me. What was God thinking? For me, understanding Him was vital at that time. I went to Institute and learned about the history of the Church, the history of all churches. I went to the Catholic seminary to learn about the Catholic Church. I went to learn about everything that I could put my hands on. That brought me closer to God. I learned Hebrew and Greek. I learned the New Testament’s actual language and learned the Torah in its native language. All this has helped me understand God more. <br /><br /> 
                </span>

                <span id="Exclusive_Quote_Mod_in_SM">
