                </span>

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                This whole event may seem like it’s a disaster to a lot of humans, but to me, it was a growing experience. It helped me learn, number one, about the communication problem between me and my husband, and that human communication is not just verbal, but that body language, the atmosphere, everything is also part of communication. That helped me understand humans more. I realized that I’m such a scientist; I’m not that human myself. It made me understand who I am and made me understand the other side of the world. <br /><br /> 

                There are feelings in this world, there are people that value a lot of things more than I do. I read a lot of books during that time. I must have read 100 books. It was a lot of books! I still remember one book, written by a businessman. It said that a person is a bag of emotions. They are not a bag of logic that you put together, that you can delineate. They are not robots; they are bags of emotions, and you’re dealing with a bunch of emotions around you. It was an eye-opener for me. <br /><br /> 

                This ordeal also helped me learn about God, learn about Jesus, learn about why things happen, learn about how people feel, how people get hurt, how I have hurt other people all my life, how it feels to hurt someone, and how it feels to be hurt. To me, it was a very valuable experience, even though it is such a horrible thing to have happen to you. My changing and understanding my own fault and deficiencies made me more able to forgive, and Norman also somehow turned around. <br /><br /> 

                He returned to his senses and decided to come back home and come back to the family. My children love him and wanted to accept him. He’s back in the family and my commitment to God is a lot stronger. Now I realize God has given us unconditional love and is waiting for me to understand who I am and how I can improve myself. He has spent so much time and energy and created all of these things around me so I can grow and learn more. <br /><br /> 

                Each day I learn more it is because God is so forgiving. He creates opportunity for me to learn. If he stood in front of me and said, “Listen, Evelyn, you have to learn about God. You have to learn about Jesus. You have to believe in me,” no. I wouldn’t have listened! People could have come to me and said, “Be good,” and I wouldn’t have listened. But when I was not good, he gave me opportunities to learn and change and come to the realization that the more evil I am, I begin to meet more evil people, and the more angelic I am, I begin to meet more angelic people. <br /><br /> 

